The '''Edinburgh Handedness Inventory''' is a measurement scale used to assess the dominance of a person's right or [[Left-handedness|left hand]] in everyday activities, sometimes referred to as [[laterality]]. The inventory can be used by an observer assessing the person, or by a person self-reporting hand use. The latter method tends to be less reliable due to a person over-attributing tasks to the dominant hand.
The Edinburgh Handedness Inventory was published in 1971 by R.C. Oldfield<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Oldfield |first1=RC |date=March 1971 |title=The assessment and analysis of handedness: The Edinburgh inventory |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=97–113 |pmid=5146491 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(71)90067-4}}</ref> and has been used in various scientific studies<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Verdino |first1=M |last2=Dingman |first2=S |title=Two measures of laterality in handedness: the Edinburgh Handedness Inventory and the Purdue Pegboard test of manual dexterity |journal=Perceptual and Motor Skills |volume=86 |issue=2 |date=April 1998 |pages=476–8 |pmid=9638746 |doi=10.2466/pms.1998.86.2.476}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first1=S |last1=Knecht |first2=B |last2=Dräger |first3=M |last3=Deppe |first4=L |last4=Bobe |first5=H |last5=Lohmann |first6=A |last6=Flöel |first7=E-B |last7=Ringelstein |first8=H |last8=Henningsen |date=December 2000 |title=Handedness and hemispheric language dominance in healthy humans |journal=Brain |volume=123 |pages=2512–8 |doi=10.1093/brain/123.12.2512 |url=http://brain.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/123/12/2512 |accessdate=2009-04-08 |pmid=11099452 |issue=12}}</ref> as well as popular literature.<ref>{{cite book|title=A left-handed Turn Around the World |last1=Wolman |first1=David |author1-link=David Wolman |isbn=978-0-306-81498-3 |date=2006}}</ref>
