{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} {{spanish name 2|Real|Casillas}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Jesús Bracamontes | image = | image_size = | fullname = Jesús Bracamontes Zenizo | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|12|24|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Guadalajara]], [[Mexico]] | position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]] | currentclub = | years1 = 1981–1983 | clubs1 = [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]]<ref>http://www.mediotiempo.com/jugador/futbol/jesus-bracamontes/estadisticas</ref> | caps1 =24 | goals1 =1 | manageryears1 = 1989–1990 | managerclubs1 = [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]] | manageryears2 = 1991–1993 | managerclubs2 = [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]] | manageryears3 = 1994–1995 | managerclubs3 = [[Correcaminos UAT|UAT]] | manageryears4 = 1995–1996 | managerclubs4 = [[Estudiantes Tecos|UAG]] | manageryears5 = 1996 | managerclubs5 = [[Monarcas Morelia|Morelia]] | manageryears6 = 2000–2001 | managerclubs6 = [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]] | club-update = | nationalteam-update = }}
'''Jesús Bracamontes Zenizo''' ({{IPA-es|xeˈsuz βɾakaˈmonte<!-- Yes, without the final /s/ - it is elided before the initial /s/ of "Zenizo". --> seˈniso}};<ref>The corresponding European Spanish pronunciation is {{IPA-es|xeˈsuz βɾakaˈmontes<!-- Here the final /s/ is retained because of the following /θ/, which is a different consonant. --> θeˈniθo|}}. In isolation, ''Jesús'' and ''Bracamontes'' are pronounced, respectively, {{IPA-es|xeˈsus|}} and {{IPA-es|bɾakaˈmontes|}} in both Mexican and European Spanish.</ref> born in [[Guadalajara, Jalisco]]) is a Mexican former [[Association football|football]] coach.
== Career == He gained prominence as the coach of [[C.D. Guadalajara|Club Deportivo Guadalajara]] in the 1990s. He also served as assistant coach for the [[Mexico national football team]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ex-Chivas coach in S.A. on Saturday |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SAEC&p_theme=saec&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10630863D9F4CD70&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date=5 November 2004 |publisher=San Antonio Express-News }}</ref>
Bracamontes later worked as a Football analyst along with [[Pablo Ramírez]] for the TV station [[Univision]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/losangeles/stories/2006/05/08/daily15.html |date=9 May 2006 |publisher=Los Angeles Business |title=Univision unveils World Cup announce teams}}</ref><ref>[http://futbol.univision.com/fifacopamundial/familia-univision/article/2009-12-17/jesus-el-profe-bracamontes-el#axzz2H1TejQyd Interview with Bracamontes]</ref>
== Family == Jesús is the father of [[Jacqueline Bracamontes]], an actress and model who became famous after representing Mexico at the [[Miss Universe 2001]] contest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cronica.com.mx/nota.php?id_nota=480200 |date=11 January 2010 |publisher=La cronica de hoy |language=Spanish |title=Dice Jacqueline Bracamontes que está soltera y feliz}}</ref> His son is named after him.
Wife of Jesús is Jacqueline van Hoorde, who is of Belgian descent.
Jesús is also the oldest brother of Former player and coach [[Carlos Bracamontes]].
