'''Sir Theodosius Edward Allesley Boughton''' (1760 – 30 August 1780) was the [[Rouse-Boughton baronets|7th Boughton baronet of Lawford]] who was poisoned by his brother-in-law in circumstances which made the case famous in its time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bevan|first1=G. Phillips|title=Tourist's Guide to Warwickshire|date=1882|publisher=Edward Standford|location=London|isbn=0554808021}}</ref>  At the age of 21, Boughton stood to inherit a fortune, which in the event of his death before that age would pass to his sister.

Boughton was confined to his bed by severe illness at Lawford Hall, [[Little Lawford]], near [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]] where his mother and sister, Mrs Donellan wife of Captain John Donellan, were living. He died shortly after taking a draught from the hands of Lady Boughton complaining of the unpleasant taste.<ref>The Murder of Sir Theodosius Boughton; http://yearofdeaths.blogspot.co.uk/2012/02/murder-of-sir-theodosius-boughton-1780.html</ref>

After his body was exhumed on a suspicion of poisoning, a Coroner's inquest returned a verdict of murder against Captain Donellan. Captain Donellan, who was known as Diamond Donellan, because of a large diamond he had brought back from India, was tried, condemned and executed on 2 April 1781 <ref>John Donellan, Esq; http://www.exclassics.com/newgate/ng359.htm</ref> for the crime although the evidence against him was solely circumstantial and he died solemnly protesting his innocence.<ref name=Cooke>{{cite book|last1=Cooke|first1=Elizabeth|title=The damnation of John Donellan :a mysterious case of death and scandal in Georgian England|date=2011|publisher=Profile|isbn=9781846684821}}</ref>  His widow subsequently married [[Leigh baronets|Sir Egerton Leigh Bt]].<ref>''Burke's Peerage''</ref><ref>[[Peter Burke (barrister)|Peter Burke]] (1849), ''Celebrated Trials Connected with the Aristocracy in the Relations of Private Life''. William Benning</ref><ref>Cooke (2011) pp.227-229</ref>

The title was inherited by a half cousin, (grandson of the 4th Baronet by his second wife Catherine<ref>Cooke (2011) p.87</ref>), Sir Edward Boughton, 8th Baronet, who sold Lawford Hall (later demolished) and the Warwickshire estate in 1793.<ref>Cooke (2011) pp.224-225</ref>

